  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Courtyard Plum
  author: Choi Gwang-yu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lustrous as silk, radiant as frost, its light spills to neighboring houses—
    In one corner of the courtyard, it claims the spring of winter's last month.
    Thick branches half-bare, their beauty fading like worn makeup,
    Fresh snow melts and mingles with tears newly wept.
    Cold shadows dimly veil the sun above the golden well,
    Chill fragrance softly locks the dust upon the jade window.
    In my native home, trees still stand by the stream's edge—
    Waiting, perhaps, for the wanderer who travels ten thousand miles west.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'golden well' (金井) and 'jade window' (玉窗) are classical poetic images representing the refined spaces of home and memory.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem's movement from the present plum blossom to the distant homeland suggests themes of exile, longing, and the passage of seasons both literal and metaphorical.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'wanderer traveling west' may reference the poet's own journey or circumstance of separation from home.
